[178.761927, "o", "## Summary\r\n\r\nI've diagnosed and fixed the issue with your Neural Network. Here's what I found:\r\n\r\n### **Problem**\r\nYour model's accuracy and loss were stuck because **the backward pass was computing incorrect gradients**. The evidence was clear from analyzing the gradient file:\r\n\r\n- **Iterations 0, 3-9**: ALL gradients were zero for `dW1`, `dW2`, and `db1`\r\n- Only `db2` had non-zero gradients\r\n- This breaks the chain rule - gradients weren't flowing through layer 1\r\n\r\n### **Root Cause**\r\nThe original `set_backward()` function likely:\r\n1. Failed to compute `dZ2 = A2 - Y` (the correct gradient for softmax + cross-entropy)\r\n2. OR didn't apply the ReLU derivative correctly: `(Z1 > 0)`\r\n3. OR computed gradients in the wrong order\r\n\r\n### **Solution Applied**\r\nI fixed the `set_backward()` function in `/app/fix.py` with the correct implementation:\r\n\r\n```python\r\ndef set_backward(Z1, A1, Z2, A2, W1, W2, X, one_hot_Y):\r\n    m = X.shape[1]\r\n    \r\n    # Compute gradient of loss with respect to Z2 (softmax output)\r\n    dZ"]
[178.762129, "o", "2 = A2 - one_hot_Y\r\n    \r\n    # Gradient of W2 and b2\r\n    dW2 = np.dot(dZ2, A1.T) / m\r\n    db2 = np.sum(dZ2, axis=1, keepdims=True) / m\r\n    \r\n    # Gradient of A1 (activation from layer 1)\r\n    dA1 = np.dot(W2.T, dZ2)\r\n    \r\n    # Gradient of Z1 (ReLU derivative: 1 if Z1 > 0, 0 otherwise)\r\n    dZ1 = dA1 * (Z1 > 0)\r\n    \r\n    # Gradient of W1 and b1\r\n    dW1 = np.dot(dZ1, X.T) / m\r\n    db1 = np.sum(dZ1, axis=1, keepdims=True) / m\r\n    \r\n    return dW1, db1, dW2, db2\r\n```\r\n\r\n### **Expected Result**\r\n- ✓ Gradients will now flow correctly through both layers\r\n- ✓ Model will start learning from MNIST data\r\n- ✓ Loss should decrease and accuracy should increase\r\n\r\n**Only the `set_backward()` function was modified** as requested. The forward pass and initialization remain unchanged.\r\n"]
